{"parse":{"title":"Friendship bench","pageid":7332678,"revid":832837006,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-content\" role=\"presentation\"><tbody><tr><td class=\"mbox-image\"><div style=\"width:52px\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Ambox_important.svg/40px-Ambox_important.svg.png\" width=\"40\" height=\"40\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Ambox_important.svg/60px-Ambox_important.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b4/Ambox_important.svg/80px-Ambox_important.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"40\" data-file-height=\"40\" /></div></td><td class=\"mbox-text\"><div class=\"mbox-text-span\">This article <b>needs attention from an expert in Education</b>.<span class=\"hide-when-compact\"> Please add a <i>reason</i> or a <i>talk</i> parameter to this template to explain the issue with the article. <a href=\"/wiki/Wikipedia:WikiProject_Education\" title=\"Wikipedia:WikiProject Education\">WikiProject Education</a> may be able to help recruit an expert.</span>  <small><i>(November 2008)</i></small></div></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The \"Friendship Bench\" is a tool for positive mental and emotional health used in various settings.\n</p><p>In Zimbabwe, the Friendship Bench approach to therapy uses listening and \"problem-solving therapy\" by trained lay-counselor grandmothers.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  When seeking mental health care is stigmatized or resources are not available\u2014Zimbabwe has just 12 psychiatrists for 14 million people<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\u2014the Friendship Bench offers what so far seems to be an effective and simple option.  Depression is referred to as  <i>kufungisisa,</i> \u201cthinking too much,\" in the Shona language.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In a school setting a <b>friendship bench</b> may also be known as a <b>buddy bench</b>, and is a special place in a <a href=\"/wiki/School\" title=\"School\">school</a> <a href=\"/wiki/Playground\" title=\"Playground\">playground</a> where a child can go when they want someone to talk to.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Friendship benches may be distinctively different from other seating in the <a href=\"/wiki/School\" title=\"School\">school</a> and may be specially designed by an artist or with the help of the children themselves. They are rainbow colored and were originally created by C.R Plastics, a Canadian company that creates recycled plastic outdoor furniture. Such benches are situated in open and well-travelled areas of the school so that any child using the bench will be noticed quickly.\n</p><p>When a <a href=\"/wiki/Child\" title=\"Child\">child</a> feels the need for a friend to talk to, he or she can show this by using the friendship bench. Other children and staff will recognise this as a sign that some help, support or comfort is needed and will come to talk with the child.\n</p><p>The friendship bench is a means by which a child can seek support without the need to rationalise their feelings or to seek-out a particular member of staff or special friend. Because the bench is in the day-to-day environment of the school it can be used at any time and for any reason\u2014from seemingly trivial matters to more serious concerns\u2014and encourages children to ask for help when they are troubled.\n</p><p>The Friendship Benches were originally created in 2012 by a fifth grader, at the time, Acacia Woodley. Acacia now speaks at schools across North America and is very happily the founder and CEO of company, Tiny Girl, Big Dream.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Friendship_bench&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Ridgwell, Henry. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.voanews.com/a/zimbabwe-friendship-bench-mental-health-treatment/3661639.html\">\"Zimbabwe Tackles Mental Health With 'Friendship Benches<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">'</span>\"</a>. <i>VOA</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-01-16</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=VOA&amp;rft.atitle=Zimbabwe+Tackles+Mental+Health+With+%27Friendship+Benches%27&amp;rft.aulast=Ridgwell&amp;rft.aufirst=Henry&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.voanews.com%2Fa%2Fzimbabwe-friendship-bench-mental-health-treatment%2F3661639.html&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AFriendship+bench\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation news\">Ridgwell, Henry. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.voanews.com/a/zimbabwe-friendship-bench-mental-health-treatment/3661639.html\">\"Zimbabwe Tackles Mental Health With 'Friendship Benches<span style=\"padding-right:0.2em;\">'</span>\"</a>. <i>VOA</i><span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">2018-01-16</span></span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%